DNC just loosened the qualifications for the 4th Democratic presidential debate (to be held in October) [1]. The starting date for the 2% polling number is June 28, the same starting date as the 3rd debate qualification. This modification essentially means all those qualified for the 3rd debate will qualify for the 4th debate, AND gives more time for those that did not qualify for the 3rd debate.

There are only 7 candidates who have an approval rating of over 2%, which is required to qualify for the next debate in September. With that next debate being the 3rd out of 4 I see those candidates who have spent a lot of time and money but have yet to see any promising results to start to pull out of the race. To pull out in August would give that candidate plenty of time to regroup and focus on more accomplish-able goals and to boost their approval rating in their respected areas. I see more dropping out of the race after the 3rd debate but August will hold plenty of weight when it comes to who is the front runner for the Democratic party.

It is impossible to CHOMP this question. This is purely a question of money and motivation and Moulton,Sestak,Delaney,Willamson, a no name candidate, and Bennet,Hickenlooper, Ryan,Inslee,Williamson, Bullock and Steyer all have plausible reasons to continue. For the Congressmen,Governors,and Senators, I assumed that all like Swallwell would make a rational decision and leave with dignity and money intact. All will but the timing of this question makes the precise timing unascertainable. As of now 18 of 20 appeared at the labor union forum.All are scheduled to appear at all upcoming events in Iowa and New Hampshire. Now we have 3 mass shootings in a week including one 8 blocks from my office at the Gilroy Garlic Festival. Media coverage is 24/7 and all but Sestak no name, have all been given free appearances on Democratic TV (MSNBC) and CNN (Fake News). Even Williamson who would be more likely to be at a seance,seminar,or paid speech or ministering to Oprah, was given 5 minutes of fame by Anderson Cooper and the subject of a glowing article by David Brooks. Truly with ubiquitous media coverage and little to cover in August,all have access to the bully pulpit. Then an entirely predictable series of mass murders gives them all something intensely passionate to talk about and the media to cover at least for a month,maybe 2 weeks,see Newtown. Then Iowa and New Hampshire are like rotten boroughs, small, extremely idiosyncratic, with a sometimes roulette result. Who ever heard of Jimmy Carter,Howard Dean, and Eugene McCarthy or Pat Buchanan before these events which have an outsized influence and any candidate can catch fire and win becoming Frontrunner. The winner in Iowa wins the nomination since Carter. Fly too close to the sun like Icarus and Howard Dean you scream and plummet like a rock. Frankly,I blame Tom Perez and the DNC for this roulette and circular firing squad. Just like Presidency we have 50 different elections to get into the Superbowl and it's almost like a lottery. So I have reduced my forecast to 90 percent and move towards the crowd. @Emil may well be right But the volatility of the crowd stats indicates that as always its Fox and Hedge Hawg so I reduce forecast of 95 to 90 and await future developments.

The eight that have qualified have no reason to quit. Julian Castro and Andrew Yang will likely make the debate, as well as Tulsi Gabbard (and if she doesn't, she could try a third party bid). Inslee and Bullock have incentives to stay in (Inslee needs to keep pushing on climate to maybe become energy secretary, Bullock appealed to some voters in the second debate and is well received in Iowa) and not many to leave. Hickenlooper could run for senate, and doesn't have much left for him in the race. Tim Ryan will probably want to run for his house seat again. Delaney, Gillibrand, Williamson, De Blasio, and Bennet all lack clear incentives to leave the race this early, but also could leave because of exhaustion and the perceived futility of their run (depending on the candidate).

I suspect at least Hickenlooper or Ryan, if not both, will drop out due to near certainty of missing the next debate and lack of traction. I feel there’s a fair likelihood that at least one or two others who miss the next debate (likely 8-10 of those in the second debate) will also drop out, possibly just before the next debate once the time to qualify passed, while the rest stubbornly stay in or give the news that they’re dropping out during or immediately after the third debates to minimize the media attention on their dropout. I think there’s an equal chance of many more dropping out or none at all. Will do more analysis later.
